segments.text: July and August and early September, it makes you begin to think about a college education that's going to be a better route.
I was not adverse to hard work later on.
I deeply appreciated it because I knew how to work hard in the classroom and later in career.
Describe, I have not had such a conversation with anyone about med school before.
Describe how you and the other members of that entering class, how you were gathered, how did the year begin, how did y'all get into classes and so forth.
Well it was interesting because at this same time A&M was undergoing the transition from non-compulsory
or two non-compulsory corps, and the admission of women.
And the very first young woman to ever go through veterinary college was in my class.
There were 63 young men and one young lady.
And we did have orientation for it.
We had a full day orientation prior to the start of classes.
And of course, when you're here on campus and you're talking to all the veterinary students, you know a whole lot.
The word of mouth on campus is probably the best communication link there is.
So we knew what to expect.
We knew how hard it was going to be.
We knew what the long hours would be.
And we also
just assembled as a group.
And with only 64 people, you get to know each other very quickly.
And I had had classes with so many of the others in my first class.
You also had friends that you left behind that didn't get in.
They didn't have the grades to get in.
Many of them were going to go another year and to keep trying to get in.
And we knew what we were in for to some degree.
But we were also in another transition.
We were in the transition to the three year, year round, nine trimesters of work, which is actually one more comparable to semester credit hours than the four years at two.
And we knew we were in for long hours the entire year.
We only got a small time off of about two weeks
in August, so it was grueling.
We had 39 contact hours in class my first semester, and on Fridays we had nine hours of class.
We started every Friday morning for 15 weeks with a retroactive exam in microbiology.
and anatomy lab from 1 to 5 on Friday afternoons.
And one Friday afternoon, about three quarters through the semester, one of our classmates threw up his arms.
He said, that's it.
I can't take anymore.
I'm gone.
And we never saw him again.
Oh, really?
Back to that orientation.
I've heard that Al Price used to give an impressive... Oh, clearly he was an impressive individual.
And I will tell you, I had always had an interest since a small boy of being a scientist, of being in science, of accomplishing something that would be known, of achieving some things big.
And when Al Price gave the orientation and often would come speak to us as a class, I thought, I want to be a dean.
I want to be in a leadership role
in veterinary medicine.
I'm not sure at that point I had the vision of then going higher up in upper administration.
I later got that vision.
But he was so professional and made such an impact, I believe, on all 64 of us about the trust that had been given to us.
about the select few out of the 600, here we were the 64, that we had a real obligation and responsibility to not only ourselves and our parents, but to this institution.
And you could not help but want to achieve because of how he laid things out and just the overall role model professionalism that was before us.
Now, I've heard that he gave an emphasis on pronouncing the name of the profession correctly.
No question.
It was veterinary medicine, and it was a veterinarian, and that was very clear.
And you need to learn to spell it correctly.
And back then, most of the times, even in the sciences, if you misspelled a word, it may be counted off.
And boy, those medical terms were not easy.
Now, his nickname was Slick Al.
Slick Al.
What did that mean?
It was given before we got there, and I think, I never heard a lot of people discuss it, but I think that he was just so smooth in how he handled himself.
That it wasn't that he was a slick operator putting one over?
No, absolutely not.
And you knew he was
He was tough, he was straight, he was forward, and he was professional in every way.
And I think it was a compliment, quite frankly, because he operated everything so smoothly and in such incredible order.
That first year, did you all take all the same courses?
Absolutely.
We all had the same courses.
But we had a little bit different schedules because we were broken into two sections of 32.
What were the, as you now look back, what were the toughest?
Oh, that's easy.
The toughest courses were anatomy and physiology.
Who taught those?
Big John Miloff.
And we called him Big John.
He was about 6'4", just a,
tremendous teacher.
And when he walked in, he commanded respect.
And I'll never forget one day, one of my classmates asked him in histology lab, which we got only three hours of credit.
He said, Dr. John, why is this just a three hour credit course?
Because we were putting in many more hours.
He said, well, son,
We didn't want you taking too damn many hours this semester.
That was his answer, and it was dropped then.
And the other was clearly physiology.
Who taught that?
This one had a nickname.
Great teacher, he's now deceased.
His name was Dick Davis.
Brilliant man.
Could have taught in any medical school in the world.
And he would get so excited in labs that he would almost froth at the mouth.
And he was nicknamed Mad Dog Davis.
And I'm sure that came because of his excitement.
And he would just get so excited.
And he had another professor with him that helped in labs.
His last name was Sabonowicz.
And that may be Polish, I think.
But it was some Eastern European country.
And the two of them would just, I mean, get into a comic situation over something happening with a dog on the physiograph in a physiology laboratory doing an experiment.
We were just amazed at it, but boy, they were good.
And was there any course that was fun?
What was the most enjoyable of those?
I loved the sciences.
And I really enjoyed physiology.
To me, it was fun because you would, for the first time, you get your hands on some animals, you could see the physiologic responses and systems of the body and the intricacies of how they worked.
To me, it was the most fun course.
It was a difficult course.
Anatomy was something you knew you had to learn, but it wasn't very exciting.
And I think the people who taught it would probably tell you that.
I enjoyed biochemistry because I had another course of it in the first year.
It was a tough course, but it was fundamental.
The first year, both semesters or all three trimesters as I had it, you were really laying the foundations and the basics for what you really, in your mind, thought you were there to do.
And you had to keep reminding yourself that I've got to accomplish this before I get to do the things of hands-on experiences.
Now, over on the campus, part of the campus where I was working then, we posted grades publicly.
Oh, absolutely.
Is that right?
Oh, yeah, we did too.
All right, at the end of that first semester in general, what was the result for your class?
I don't think we lost anyone except the young man that was just so burned out he left.

I don't recall losing anyone the whole first year because they clearly had the aptitude to be able to handle it because when you take 64 out of 600, you've got people there who have the intellect to handle it.
And I don't recall anybody, but it was always interesting to go look because your grades were posted and your name was up there.
Do you have any generalization about what kind of GPA, if we went to the bottom of the 64, the GPA was what or higher probably?
I seriously would doubt anyone was in that class that was lower than 33.
I would not think so.
Now what was interesting was that all the high achievers were now put in there together and being challenged by professors that wanted to see how much they could challenge them.
And for some of the people in the class to make their first C or D just absolutely crushed them.
generalize about the makeup of the class.
Where were they from geographically?
All of them were from all parts of the state except for nine that were contract students from the state of Louisiana.
And they were all different.
And many of them were truly Cajun.
And they taught Cajun.
They brought their chicory coffee with them in the morning.
But they were great to have with us.
And they mixed in
with us.

It was interesting because the student composition of that 64 was made up of a lot of us that were very young, and a lot of students who already had a degree, a lot who had been out and worked for a number of years.
We had people in my class, I'm sure, who were in their 30s, and yet here I was
I got my undergraduate and my doctorate at the age of 23.
So we were young, a lot of us.
So there was a big mixture, and many of them were married with children.
There were many of us that were looking for a wife.
And so where were the Texans from?
All over the state.
I mean, it was really varied.
One of my classmates my first year in veterinary college was from Sterling City.
And one of my dear friends that housed next door was from Miami, Texas, way up in the panhandle.
Were most of them small town, rural?
I would say probably a higher percentage then than you would find today, yeah.
Probably 60, 65%.
But that was also true of the whole student body, too.
What was life like for that one young lady?

You know that was interesting because if you look back at the 1963 annual you will see a full-page picture of me holding the door open for her walking into the small animal clinic and I think it signified and she understood that she had opened a new door.
But she was
a unique personality that enjoyed that position.
And we treated her with great respect.
She took a lot of joking, but it was never done in a way that she shouldn't be here.
It was done in a way of, hey, you know, you're the first to do this.
We're glad to have you.
And she had the personality to just mix in
like one of everyone else.
What was her name?
Her name was Sonia Oliphant.
O-L-I-P-H-A-N-T?
That's correct.
Do you remember from where or what school?
I'm not totally sure.
I think it may have been Texas Tech.
And I know that she later married
a student that was in a class or two behind us and was in practice in the Lubbock area.
So she did graduate.
She graduated with us right on time.
And so in the four years, or three years, she, as far as you were aware, was not treated inappropriately?
Never, that I was aware of.
I mean, she was included in everything.
It was kind of like we were proud to have her.
I really believe that that was part of the mentality of our class, that women were coming to A&M, she was the first in our veterinary class, and we were glad to have her.
She was a good sport.
personality and just mixed in with all of them.
Now how did you all create a kind of community of friends?
Did you do anything socially in your class?
Oh yeah, and the veterinary college was well organized.
The student body was well organized.
We had what we call the student chapter of the American Veterinary Medical Association.
And secondly, each class had its class officers.
We had certain kinds of class functions and events.
We had a mixer and a big barbecue at the start of our very first trimester.
And that was for the whole student body.
We would have class meetings.
Where would it be held?
It was held out at Old Fort Shiloh once.
It was held over near Snook once.
It was held over where

current Texas Hall of Fame is and I'm trying to recall but I believe the second year class was responsible for putting it on for the first so that when you got to be the next year you put it on for that class.
To whom did you turn for advice if you needed?
You were assigned an advisor, an academic advisor who was a full

tenure track faculty member in the college of veterinary medicine and if you had any kind of problem or need you went to that individual as well as with only 64 students the dean's office uh dr mcmurray usually was available can you give an example of any advice you've sought and received i don't recall ever going things went smoothly and
I don't recall ever having to go because we knew what our schedule was going to be.
It was sent to us then.
We didn't go negotiate it.
Did you have a car by then?
That first year in Vetchco?
Yes.
I finally had a car.
And you lived where?
I lived still in Law Hall my first year.
I lived off campus my second
over on College Main.
And then my third year, I lived out at Welburton in an old house with three other veterinary students.
I was the cook and they became the cleanup crew.
And we could save tremendous amounts of money.
Because we'd go to the grocery store and buy our food and I'd cook.
That first year of vet school, how often did you go home?
Not much.
I probably didn't go home, but maybe once or twice.
You're saying maybe Thanksgiving and Christmas?
Yeah, and I recall, I know I went home the weekend that Kennedy was assassinated because I got back to the room.
I had the radio on.
Maybe they had announced it.
over the loudspeakers at veterinary school.
But I remember getting in my car and driving home, listening to the radio, and almost having trouble driving, trying to stay concentrated to the happenings that were occurring.
And then that shooting of Jack Ruby in the police station occurred while some of us were in church Sunday morning.
And I was at home.
And I remember seeing that on television at home.
before I drove back.
This doesn't have anything to do with vet school, but does the real world.
What was the reaction of you and your buddies to those events?
I think everyone was just in a state of disbelief and almost shocked that that could occur, particularly that it could occur in Texas.
Because I want to tell you, there is a Texas pride that is inborn and it is there forever.
See, I was embarrassed.
Absolutely.
And I think we all felt that way.
I had a 12-to-1 class, and I was to meet Garland Bayless, and we were going to the MSC.
And I came in, and he was glued to this radio.
And I said, come on, we've got to beat the line.
He said, listen to the radio.
I said, we can hear the darn radio.
He said, listen.
And I heard Cronkite say, I've just been given the notice.
President Kennedy is dead.
And my, my, my, I was stunned.
The route, let's go back to a typical day while you, that first year of vet school.
You got up, did you eat breakfast in the dining hall?
I usually ate sabisa.
And then went to climb.
Immediately went across the tracks.
At that time we were the only
academic program across the tracks.
And you, where'd you eat lunch?
Normally, we would come to Northgate or maybe go to Savisa the first year.
Later on, when we lived off campus or when I lived out at Welbert, we actually made our lunches
and ate under the trees around the veterinary college.
Normally you were over there in the afternoons until about what time?
Oh, at least 5 o'clock.
Did you go back at night much?
Not a whole lot.
Rarely did I go back.
Every once in a while I'd have to go to the library, and we did have the veterinary medical library, which is now the medical sciences library.
and if I had to do some research or something.
I never could study very well in the library.

My personal best study was done to get in my room, close the doors, get it quiet, and believe it or not, I usually studied laying on the bed, sometimes laying on the bed with my notes in the floor and looking off on them.
And did you have any Saturday classes over there?
No, we had no Saturday classes until my senior year.
What did you all do on Saturdays?
Well Friday night was an off night.
We rested, re-relaxed, we were dead.
Saturday a lot of times we'd sleep in a little later.
Of course we'd be involved with campus activities.
And then a lot of times on Saturday nights we'd be back studying because we had so many major things happening.
It was an accelerated program on the three year transition.
Did many vet students party?
on a Saturday night?
Some did, but not like probably a lot of other students.
As far as you know, if they were going to party, where did they go?
Oh, gosh, what was the name of that place out on Highway 60?
Not Uncle Ed's.
No.
Went to Whiskey Bridge.
No, it was someplace out there.
I never did go out there, but I can remember going out there.
I remember talking about Whiskey Bridge.
There was someplace out there that a lot of them went.
Lakeview Club, I think, was open, so a few of them would go out there.
How many of your classmates were smokers?
That's an interesting question.
There were probably, out of 64, I would say we probably had 15 maybe.
Oh, that's all?
Maybe 20.
But I tell you what, when they took histology and Dr. John Miliff showed them the inside of a smoker's lung, there were more of them that quit after that, after seeing what it would do.
And he also showed them the lung tissue of a person with emphysema.
And that spoke volumes because you were looking through a microscope
at what it would do to the body and to the lungs.
Did you and your buddies even know the terminology of drugs?
No, you never heard of it.
The only drug everyone back then was aware of was alcohol.
One thing we did on Friday nights, or Saturday nights, the old Circle drive-in was still there, so we'd go to a drive-in movie.
Every once in a while we'd drive over to Sam Houston.
Now you met this special young lady your first year of vet school?
My second.
Second year.
And you began to see her more often.
Absolutely.
When did it get serious?
It wasn't long.
I met her in October.
I went to Austin for the UT A&M game.

in November on Thanksgiving and met her parents that short period and then in December I actually went she was from Dilley down in South Texas and I actually went down where she lived and visited their family then and then the very next year she graduated the University of Texas in May and uh

in Corpus and of course we were already real serious then and that was not working out because Corpus was so far away and there was no way and I was in my senior year by then there was no way I could go see her and of course she couldn't come up here every weekend
And her lights went out on her car returning to Corpus one weekend after being up here for a football game.
So in October of my senior year, before I graduated the next August, we decided that we were going to get married.
And we just prayed that she could find a teaching job at Bryan College Station.
And her mother and dad came in October for a football game here.
And by that time, she had another brother here.
And down at the old Bryan Holiday Inn, which is now a private dorm, I asked everybody to leave the room, and I talked to her dad and asked permission to marry her.
I had already given her the ring earlier that weekend.
And he gave us our blessings, and we got married in December.
That same year?
Of your fourth year in vet school.
Third year in vet school.
Third year in vet school.
It was December 26, 1965.
All right, and so then she is here teaching?
She started teaching here in January at Bowie, Bowie Elementary in downtown Bryant.
So your fourth year, I mean, you're, oh, no.
My senior year, third year.
Yeah, yeah, you're finishing.
Right.
At that point, who had influenced, which individual or what course had influenced you most in the DVM program?
That's easy.
I was influenced by just the excitement
the challenge, the glamour of small animal surgery.
Because what was so exciting was that we were doing then and implementing and bringing
the surgical procedures that were being done in the human to the small animal, and people were willing to pay for it.
I'm talking about cataract surgery, I'm talking about all kinds of orthopedic surgery, and my heart and my interest was in spinal and neurosurgery.
And there was a professor named Don Piermatti who was probably one of the most professional individuals I was ever around.
and his influence of scrubbing in with him.
And two things happened that year.
One is that Rudder's dog, Old Ranger, who was the campus mascot.
And when I was an undergrad here, we would take him and put him in the seat in a classroom with us.
And he always was over there.
We'd wait for him to cross the street.
We'd take him into Sabisa.
He got a kidney stone.
And I got to scrub in on that procedure.
And then later in the year, Reveille had some surgical problem that I don't recall specifically what it was now.
I also got to scrub in on that.
And I just have always been a person driven by challenge.
That's why I could never have been in a routine private practice.
It would have bored me to death.
And when I could see the challenge of what they were doing, the pioneering that could be done in it, the research that could be done in it, I was turned on to that.
And I immediately, prior to even my senior year, had begun to think about, I want to go into teaching and research.
And ultimately, I want to get into a leadership role of what's happening in this kind of an educational field.
So I had to start preparing myself for it.
So I began to look
And after graduation, where could I go and get post-doctoral training in the area where I wanted to pursue?
Who did you turn to as a counselor for those serious thoughts?
Well, Dr. Pierre Maddy was one, and Dr. Lynn Huroff was another in small animal.
And I also went to Dr. Price and talked to him about it.
And of course, it was clear that if I wanted to pursue an academic career,
that I had to go on and do post-doctoral work.
So they were very good in giving me contacts of other veterinary medical colleges around the nation.
I was given an offer to come be a post-doctoral student both at Colorado State University and at Auburn University.
I would much prefer probably to have gone to Colorado State and lived in the mountains.
But Auburn had the premier neurosurgeon in America.
And I'll never forget, they actually flew me up there to have an interview.
And it was only my second time ever in an airplane.
And they offered me the job while I was there.
which was a post-doctoral research fellow in the Scott Ritchie program.
And my salary would be $7,580 a year.
And what is amazing is that I graduated from A&E.
Because we were on.
And we loaded.
